          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Recycling with Salafy<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347'>Daniel "Dartax" Burke</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=10347&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 17, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> There is more than one way to generate card advantage. Commonly, people draw more cards. As such, card draw has seen lots of discussion on DeckTech, and in general. This is plain and simple card advantage. Players simply use spells, powers, and effects to draw as much as possible to acquire the cards they need or want.<br />
<br />
It also possible to conserve cards. Simply put, the player tries to use as few cards as possible for maximum effect. There are several ways to do this. One way is to play cards with maximum potential, although many of these cards can also have high costs such as Ormagon and Cataclysm. Another trick is to use spells/powers directly from the discard pile. Using cards in from the discard pile can easily save up cards in the hand, and it is very similar to the method I want to illustrate using Salafy, or recycling cards (in this case, creatures).<br />
<br />
Recycling cards is very similar to conserving cards. For the purposes of this article, we&#8217;ll look at recycling cards as taking cards from your discard pile and returning them to your hand. Unlike returning cards from the discard pile to the deck, this method of recycling cards often enables you to play the card that turn, or maybe on a later turn at your discretion. This is what this article will attempt to address. As a specific example, I&#8217;ll use Salafy.<br />
<br />
Salafy has a wonderful effect for recycling in a Naroom deck. Once per turn, as you play a Naroom creature, you can return a copy of that Naroom creature from your discard pile to your hand. If you want to conserve your creatures in a Naroom deck, there might not be a better magi. To those that use Salafy, I often recommend three copies of each creature in the deck whether they are common, uncommon, or rare cards. By doing this, you increase the odds you have another copy in the hand.<br />
<br />
I&#8217;ve long held that Salafy is a powerful Naroom magi. Part of why I thought this is because Naroom is a very creature dependant region. In the right deck, she practically guarantees a never ending supply of creatures. With an energize of six as well, she can play a creature nearly every turn with ease.<br />
<br />
Now, my first use of Salafy was in a furok deck. She was ideal for setting up my third magi, the uncorrupted Sperri. Because she could recycle creatures, even the furoks, Salafy would generate lots of my card advantage. As long as I kept one copy of a Naroom furok in my hand, I had no qualms about putting the other copy in play. If it was discarded, I only had to play the one in my hand to get the other back. It was a vicious cycle. Salafy even started with a Furok. While powerful on her own, she was actually being used a setup magi. When Salafy was defeated, there was usually only one Furok and one Baby Furok in the discard pile, the rest were in my hand because I was able to recycle them easily with Salafy. This meant that Sperri could easily have all three Furoks in hand after she got her starting Furok from the discard pile. Thus, Sperri was setup very nicely by Salafy.<br />
<br />
In fact, to help Salafy out, the first magi in that furok deck was a card draw magi, Chayla. While Chayla offered a soft method of card draw in her Eebits, Salafy could really hold her own by recycling what creatures I had already drawn until a powerful setup was achieved. How it worked was fairly simple. Chayla drew cards with the self-recycling Eebits to setup Salafy. As long as I drew enough cards, Salafy was almost guaranteed to have a copy in the hand for at least one creature in the discard pile. Once Chayla was defeated, Salafy would never lack for creatures, and I could play almost any Naroom creature without fear. In my most recent Salafy deck, she once again follows a card draw magi. The most interesting game, and a great illustration of what can happen, my opponent asked me at the end of the game how many Furoks (the regular one) were in my deck? My answer was three, of course. He told me that he counted over twenty Furoks played (no more than two at any given time). The answer was simple, my card draw early on had placed at least one Furok in my hand. Then, Salafy pulled one among her starting cards. All I did was always have one copy of the Furok in my hand at all times. Yes, I did play over twenty Furoks, but it was those same three cards over and over again. Salafy was recycling like mad, and won me the game too.<br />
<br />
So, what can you do besides recycle Furoks with Salafy? A great many things. She just seems predisposed to furoks because she starts with one. Twees and Eebits can actually be very nasty with Salafy as well. Many of us know that as annoying as the Eebit can be, it only takes a spell or power to make it go away. However, Salafy can recycle the Eebit that fails to bounce back to the hand on its own. All that is needed is another Eebit to be played out. It is not enough that she turns almost any Naroom creature into the Eebit&#8217;s next of kin, but she can recycle the cursed Eebit as well. That doesn&#8217;t even cover what could be done with the Twee.<br />
<br />
Now, this article has been mostly about Salafy. Then again, she is a great example of recycling. While Salafy only applies to Naroom creatures, it is still so very broad that she becomes a powerful force in almost any Naroom swarm deck. Her starting cards are great, really nice effect, and one of the better Naroom energize rates combine to make Salafy one of the better Naroom magi in my book. There are other ways to recycle, and for other regions, but it can be hard to top Salafy. If you ever need a reminder that there are other ways to gain card advantage, I recommend you find a good Salafy deck.<br />
<br />
Note:<br />
Some other recycling methods include Forgotten Tales, Rayalon, and Corathan. That would be d&#8217;Resh (currently useable with any non-Core region to fetch non-spells), Arderial/Core (spells versus non-Arderial), and Core/Orothe (anything), and in that order. There are others, but I&#8217;ll leave them for you to find or for any reviewers to add. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php?id=4995&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
